VALUES ('0ae314bc-603a-4561-bbc4-6ab165fd7e36', 'Which choice best describes the relationship between the text''s opening and its conclusion?', 'In her essay on urban soundscapes, writer 100131 argues that city planners should treat noise pollution as a public-health issue, citing studies linking traffic noise to elevated stress hormones. She describes neighborhoods where sirens, construction, and highway hum overlap for eighteen hours a day, leaving residents with fragmented sleep even when air quality meets regulatory standards. Community interviews quoted in the essay repeatedly mention difficulty concentrating at work and heightened irritability at home. The writer contrasts cosmetic beautification projects—new planters and paint—with measurable acoustic interventions such as berms, low-noise pavement, and delivery-time restrictions. She acknowledges that complete silence is impossible in dense cities, yet insists that reducing predictable high-decibel spikes could yield health benefits comparable to modest improvements in green space. Yet the authors qualify', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"It treats the author''s caution as evidence of personal indecision rather than as a deliberate rhetorical strategy the structure enacts throughout the paragraph as written here.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Partial Scope] [Narrative Speculation] Imports unsupported assumptions about author motivation or future plans."},{"id":"B","text":"It presents the counter-perspective as appearing before the consensus view, reversing the actual order of ideas in the text from established model to challenge here throughout.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Narrative Speculation] [Structural Inversion] Reverses the actual sequence of ideas the passage develops."},{"id":"C","text":"It contrasts an earlier consensus with newer findings, reconciles partial agreement with dispute, and qualifies the scope of the conclusion throughout overall in sum in context.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct (C). Correct (C). This choice matches the passage''s rhetorical architecture from framework through evidence to qualified implications."},{"id":"D","text":"It accurately describes the concession in sentence two but ignores how the passage integrates that concession into a broader qualified defense in the closing sentences overall.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Structural Inversion] [Partial Scope] Describes only part of the passage, ignoring its overall trajectory."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Step 1 — Identify the passage organization
Focus on {{yellow:quality}} in the passage. The structure item asks you to identify the passage organization before comparing choices.

Step 2 — Match structure to purpose
Compare each option against explicit textual evidence. On medium items, correct answers usually restate the passage faithfully without absolute words the text does not support.

Step 3 — Confirm the description
Choice C is correct: It contrasts an earlier consensus with newer findings, reconciles partial agreement with dispute, and qualifies the scope of the conclusion throughout overall i….

Distractor analysis:
- A: [Partial Scope] [Narrative Speculation] Imports unsupported assumptions about author motivation or future plans.
- B: [Narrative Speculation] [Structural Inversion] Reverses the actual sequence of ideas the passage develops.
- D: [Structural Inversion] [Partial Scope] Describes only part of the passage, ignoring its overall trajectory.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Text Structure and Purpose', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'TSP', NULL, 'medium', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"rw_subtype":"structure","rw_format":"passage_mc","generator":"regenerate-english-fresh.mjs","regen_seed_offset":100000,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
